Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.020 - Purpose.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.020 - Purpose.
The purpose of this title is to establish uniform rules and regulations pertaining to domestic and certain wild animals within the unincorporated area of the county. The provisions of this title may be extended to any incorporated areas within the geographic boundaries of the county provided there is an agreement between the county board of supervisors and the governing body of such city or cities to that effect. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,183,Calaveras_County.pdf,87
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.030 - De␀nitions.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.030 - De␀nitions.
As used in this title, the following terms shall be ascribed the following meanings: ""Altered"" means rendered incapable of reproduction by physical (surgical alteration or the implantation of a device) or other accepted and legally recognized methods and certified by a licensed veterinarian. ""Animal control"" means the entire program for the regulation of domestic and certain wild animals in the county. ""Animal shelter"" means the public facility or facilities furnished by the board for the safekeeping, impoundment and disposition of animals entrusted to its care as defined in this title. ""Animal permit"" means a permit, issued by the director, that authorizes a person to keep, harbor or maintain four or more dogs of at least four months of age, or five or more cats of at least four months of age for noncommercial purposes. ""At large"" means an animal off the premises of its owner, and not under restraint by means of a leash or otherwise under the immediate control of the owner. ""Assistance dog"" means any dog that is specially trained as a guide dog, signal dog or service dog (as defined in Section 54.1 of the California Civil Code) that is used by a disabled person or any dog that is being trained for such use by a bona fide trainer. ""Board"" means board of supervisors of the county. ""Capture gun"" means any rifle or pistol used to temporarily immobilize an animal with a substance approved by the Food and Drug Administration. ""Cat"" means any member of the species Felis catus; long domesticated as a pet or companion animal; it excludes other members of the family Felidae. ""Commercial"" means operated or carried on for financial gain. ""Director"" means the director of animal control of the county, his/her officers and agents. ""Dog"" means and includes members of the species Canis familiaris; long domesticated as a pet or companion animal; it excludes other members of the family Canidae. ""Domestic animal"" means cats, dogs and includes, but is not limited to: horses, donkeys, mules, burros, cattle, sheep, goats, swine, rabbits and fowl including ostriches, emus and rheas, and other animals commonly kept for domestic purposes; it does not include any animals regulated pursuant to Section 2118 of the California Fish and Game Code. ""Enclosure"" means a fence or structure suitable to prevent the entry of young children, and which is suitable to confine a vicious dog in conjunction with other measures which may be taken by the owner or keeper of the dog. The enclosure shall be designed in order to prevent the dog from escaping and shall be approved by the director. The animal(s) shall be housed pursuant to section 597t of the Penal Code. ""Foster home"" means any facility approved by the director where domestic animals are kept on a temporary basis not to exceed six months while a permanent home for such animals is sought. ""Health officer"" means the health officer of the county, his/her officers and agents. ""Humane officer"" means any person appointed pursuant to Section 14502 of the California Corporations Code. ""Impoundment"" means the taking up and confining of all animals by the director in a manner consistent with recognized standards of humane treatment. ""Kennel"" means any enclosure, premises, building, or structure, for which the director has issued a license that authorizes four or more dogs or five or more cats over the age of four months to be kept, harbored or maintained. ""Livestock"" means but is not limited to the following: horses, donkeys, mules, burros, cattle, sheep, goats, swine, rabbits and fowl including ostriches, emus and rheas, and other animals commonly kept for domestic purposes, except dogs and cats. ""Owner"" means any person, having care, custody, control, title, interest in or possession of any animal subject to regulation by this title. ""Person"" means any individual, firm, partnership, corporation, company, society or association, and every officer, agent or employee thereof. ""Pet shop"" means any person that buys, sells or boards any species of animals, whether operated separately or in connection with another business enterprise, excepting licensed kennels or for agricultural purposes. ""Police dog"" means any dog used by a duly appointed peace officer at a recognized police agency which is used in legitimate police work so long as said dog is authorized by the appointing authority. ""Potentially dangerous dog"" means any of the following: 1. Any dog which, when unprovoked, on two separate occasions within the prior thirty-six-month period, engages in any that requires a defensive action by any person to prevent bodily injury when the person and the dog are off the proper owner of the dog; 2. Any dog which, when unprovoked, bites a person causing an injury that is less than a severe injury; 3. Any dog which, when unprovoked, on two separate occasions within the prior thirty-six-month period, has killed, seriously bitten, inflicted injury, or otherwise caused injury attacking a domestic animal off the property of the owner of the dog. ""Quarantine"" means the strict confinement of an animal or animals upon the premises of the owner or other such location as directed by the health officer in an enclosed building, cage or paddock, as may be appropriate for the species. ""Ranch dog permit"" means a permit that is issued to allow a person to keep, harbor or maintain four or more dogs over four months of age in the pursuit of a legitimate livestock production endeavor. ""Rescue organization"" means a for-profit or not-for-profit entity, or a collaboration of individuals with at least one of its purposes being the sale or placement of dogs or cats that have been removed from the animal shelter or that have been previously owned by any person other than the original breeder of that dog or cat. ""Severe injury"" means any physical injury to a human being that results in muscle tears, or disfiguring, or requires multiple sutures, or corrective or cosmetic surgery. ""Vaccination"" means the inoculation of an animal against rabies with vaccine approved by, and in the manner prescribed by, the state department of public health. ""Veterinarian"" means a person licensed to practice veterinary medicine in the state of California. ""Vicious dog"" means any of the following: 1. Any dog seized under Penal Code Section 599aa and upon the sustaining of a conviction of the owner under subdivision (a) of Section 597.5 of the Penal Code; 2. Any dog which, when unprovoked, in an aggressive manner, inflicts severe injury on or kills a human being; 3. Any dog previously determined to be and currently listed as a potentially dangerous dog which, after its owner has been notified of this determination, continues the behavior described under ""potentially dangerous dog"" or is maintained in violation of Section 6.12.060 of this title. ""Wild animal"" means any of the following: 1. Any animal described in California Fish and Game Code Sections 2116 and 2118; 2. Any animal described, in any addition to Fish and Game Code Section 2118, by regulation of the Fish and Game Commission as provided in Section 2118 (j) and (k); 3. The following members of the Class Mammalia: a. Order Carnivora, expressly excepting the domestic dog Canis familiaris and the domestic cat Fells catus, but including, but not limited to, the family Felidae (such as ocelots, margays, tigers, jaguars, leopards and cougars), the family Canidae (such as wolves, dingos, coyotes, foxes and jackals), the family Pracyonidae (raccoons), and the striped skunk Mephitis mephitis; b. Order Marsupialia such as kangaroos and opossums; c. Order Chiroptera (bats); d. Order Proboscidea (elephants); e. Order Primata including, but not limited to, monkeys, chimpanzees and gorillas; 4. Any nondomestic species when kept, maintained or harbored in such a manner as to constitute the likelihood of dange animals themselves, to human beings or to the property of human beings; 5. Any species of animal which is venomous to human beings whether its venom is transmitted by bite, sting, touch or other means, except honey-producing bees. 6. Any hybrid animal which is part wild animal and is capable of transmitting rabies, except livestock hybrids, and for which no rabies prophylaxis is recognized or authorized by the state, any live monkey (nonhuman primate), raccoon, skunk, fox, poisonous snake, leopard, panther, tiger, lion, lynx, or any other warm-blooded animal which can normally be found in the wild state. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,183,Calaveras_County.pdf,1873
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.040 - Department name.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.040 - Department name.
The official name of the department charged with enforcement of this title shall be known as the ""Office of Animal Services"". The term ""animal control"", ""animal control officer"", as used throughout this title, is interchangeable with and means the same as ""animal services"". (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,186,Calaveras_County.pdf,87
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.050 - Rules and regulations.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.050 - Rules and regulations.
The board may, by resolution, promulgate necessary rules and regulations for the administration of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,186,Calaveras_County.pdf,35
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.060 - Establishment of advisory committee.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.060 - Establishment of advisory committee.
The board may, by resolution, establish an advisory committee to serve at the pleasure of the board for the purpose of making recommendations for the betterment of the animal control program. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,186,Calaveras_County.pdf,49
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.070 - Fees.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.070 - Fees.
The board may, by resolution, periodically establish a schedule of fees for all animal control activities. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,186,Calaveras_County.pdf,33
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.080 - Relief from fees during natural calamities.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.080 - Relief from fees during natural calamities.
Upon the recommendation of the director and with the approval of the board, the fees provided for by this title may be waived when the animals have been impounded because of civic disorganization, disruption, or other conditions of devastation within the county due to fire, flood, earthquake, storm, or other natural calamity. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,186,Calaveras_County.pdf,77
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.090 - Interference.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.090 - Interference.
No person shall interfere with, oppose, or resist any authorized person charged with the enforcement of this title while that person is engaged in the performance of their duties. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,186,Calaveras_County.pdf,46
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,"6.04.100 - Noti␀cation of permit or license revocation or refusal, or other action or decision.","Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.100 - Noti␀cation of permit or license revocation or refusal, or other action or decision.
The director shall deliver a notice of revocation or refusal to the permit or license holder or applicant in any one of the following ways: A. By first class or registered mail addressed to the individual as the individual's name and address appear on the permit or license or permit or license application; B. By delivering the notice to the individual, any partner or corporate officer named in the permit or license or permit or license application in person; C. By delivering the notice to any employee of the individual at the fixed place of business if specified in the permit or license or permit or license application; D. By posting the notice in a conspicuous place upon the premises of the establishment as specified in the permit or license or permit or license application affected by number, date and name and specify the grounds for which the permit was revoked or refused and be dated and signed by the director. E. The revocation or refusal shall be effective at the time written revocation or refusal is delivered personally or posted on the property or forty-eight hours after the notice is deposited in the United States mail unless the revocation or refusal states a later effective date. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,187,Calaveras_County.pdf,240
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.110 - Appeals.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.110 - Appeals.
Any person owning or having an interest in any establishment for which a permit or license was refused or revoked by the director, or is subject to any action or decision made by the director may appeal the action, decision, refusal or revocation to the board by filing a written notice of appeal stating the name and address of the appellant and his/her desire to appeal the action, decision, refusal or revocation of the permit or license to which is attached a copy of the application for the permit or license with the refusal endorsed thereon or a copy of the notice of revocation with the board within ten days following the date of the refusal or revocation. The board shall fix a date for hearing the appeal not more than thirty days following the date the notice of appeal is filed and shall mail notice of the time and place of the hearing to the person filing the notice of appeal not less than five days prior to the date of hearing. The appellant may appear in person or by counsel and present any relevant evidence relating to matter or the lack of such grounds and director may present evidence in rebuttal thereof. The hearing may be continued from time to time as deemed appropriate by the board. The board shall find and determine from the evidence and the provisions of this title whether the appeal should be granted or denied. Nothing in this title shall prevent the board from granting a variance from the terms and conditions of this title for good cause. The decision of the board shall be final. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,187,Calaveras_County.pdf,306
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.120 - Reapplication for license.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.120 - Reapplication for license.
If an application for an interim animal permit, ranch dog permit, foster care permit, commercial kennel license or private kennel license has been denied, or has been revoked, the director may refuse to accept a new application for such a permit or license unless the applicant can demonstrate to the director's satisfaction that the conditions or circumstances for which the permit or license was revoked or denied have changed to such an extent that a new application should be considered. Such application shall be considered as a new permit or license and shall conform to any new requirements that may have been adopted since such permit or license was originally issued. (Ord. 2748 § 1(part), 2004). ",Calaveras_County,187,Calaveras_County.pdf,137
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.130 - Continuation of preexisting lawful activity.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.130 - Continuation of preexisting lawful activity.
Any activity which has been licensed or otherwise expressly permitted by the director prior to the enactment of the ordinance codified in this title may continue to exist, provided: A. Such activity may not be expanded, enlarged, or increased with respect to the number of animals without strict compliance with this title; B. In the event an animal is sold, given away, impounded, dies, or is otherwise transferred, the animal shall not be replaced without strict compliance with this title; C. The continued use or activity does not become a nuisance or threat to the health, safety, and welfare of any other person or animal. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,188,Calaveras_County.pdf,138
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS,6.04.140 - Violations.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.04 - GENERAL PROVISIONS | 6.04.140 - Violations.
A. Any person violating any of the provisions of this title shall be guilty of an infraction, unless otherwise expressly provided elsewhere in this title, and shall be punished with a fine not exceeding one hundred dollars for the first conviction and a fine not exceeding two hundred dollars for a second conviction within two years. B. The third and each subsequent conviction of this title in the period of two years shall constitute a misdemeanor, and shall be punishable by fine of not more than one thousand dollars, or by imprisonment not to exceed one year, or by both such fine and imprisonment. C. Each and every day or portion thereof on which any violation of this title is committed, continued, or permitted by any person shall constitute a separate violation hereof. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,188,Calaveras_County.pdf,183
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 
Sections: ",Calaveras_County,188,Calaveras_County.pdf,3
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.010 - Director of animal services—Appointment.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.010 - Director of animal services—Appointment.
There shall be a director of animal services of the county who shall be appointed by the county executive officer. Nothing in this chapter shall limit the environmental health agency administrator from serving as the director of animal services. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3198, § 1, 2-27-2024) ",Calaveras_County,188,Calaveras_County.pdf,76
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.020 - Duties of the director.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.020 - Duties of the director.
The duties of the director shall include, but are not limited to all of the following: A. Those duties as prescribed by the laws of the state, including Sections 121575 through 121710 of the California Health and Safety Code, Section 2606.4, Title 17, California Code of Regulations as directed by the health officer, Sections 597, 597a, 597e, 597f, 5971, 597s, and 597t of the California Penal Code and all sections of the California Food and Agriculture Code pertaining to domesticated dogs and cats. B. The director shall collect all applicable fees for animal control activities as established by resolution of the board which are due and payable to the county in accordance with usual and customary accounting practices and procedures. C. The director shall enforce the provisions of this title and applicable sections of state law in the unincorporated area of the county and in any city having an agreement with the county for such enforcement. D. The director shall impound animals and/or issue citations for violations of this title and applicable provisions of state law. E. The director shall operate an animal shelter on county premises with the furnishings, supplies and equipment provided by the board. F. The director shall maintain the animal shelter in a clean and sanitary condition and ensure the humane treatment of all impounded animals pursuant to this title and all applicable state and federal laws. G. The director shall provide for the reception, holding and disposition of dogs, cats, and other companion and domestic animals at the animal shelter or other appropriate facility. H. The director shall keep accurate records on each animal taken up, medically treated, or impounded. Said records shall include all of the following: 1. The date the animal was taken up, impounded, medically treated, euthanized, or impounded; 2. The circumstances under which the animal was taken up, medically treated, euthanized, or impounded; 3. The name(s) of the person(s) who took up, medically treated, euthanized, or impounded the animal; 4. A description of any medical treatment provided to the animal and the name of the veterinarian of record; 5. The final disposition of the animal, including the name of the person(s) who redeemed, adopted, or euthanized the animal. Said records shall be maintained for a period of three years after the conclusion of the animal's impoundment. I. The director may establish policies and procedures as deemed appropriate for the fulfillment of the purpose of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,188,Calaveras_County.pdf,537
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.030 - Animal control o␀cers—Appointment and duties.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.030 - Animal control o␀cers—Appointment and duties.
Animal control officers shall be authorized by the board and appointed by and serve at the pleasure of the director, and shall be under the direct supervision of the director. The director may delegate and assign any or all of his/her duties, responsibility and authority to any or all duly appointed animal control officers for the purpose of implementing the provisions of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,189,Calaveras_County.pdf,83
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.040 - Right of entry on private premises.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.040 - Right of entry on private premises.
A. The director shall have the authority to enter upon any premises at all reasonable times to make inspections for the purpose of enforcement of this title. If any such premises are occupied, the director shall first present proper credentials and request entry. If the premises are unoccupied, the director shall first make a reasonable effort to locate the owner or other person having charge or control of such premises and request entry. If entry is refused or denied, the director shall have recourse to such remedies as are provided by law to secure entry. B. The director may examine and enter upon all private premises for enforcement of Division 105, Part 6, Chapter 1, pursuant to Section 121625 of the California Health and Safety Code (rabies), whether consensual or not. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,189,Calaveras_County.pdf,168
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.050 - Authority to pursue.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.050 - Authority to pursue.
The director shall have the authority, when in pursuit of an animal that is in violation of any provision of this title, to enter upon the property of the owner or a third person for the purpose of impounding the animal; provided that, in the course of such pursuit he/she shall exercise reasonable care to avoid causing damage to the property entered. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,83
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.060 - Firearms authorized.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.060 - Firearms authorized.
The director is authorized to carry loaded firearms, except handguns, while acting in the course and scope of his/her employment as specified in Section 12031 of the California Penal Code. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,50
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.070 - Capture gun authorized.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.070 - Capture gun authorized.
The director is authorized to employ the use of a capture gun or any such device commonly used to immobilize animals provided such devices are authorized for use in the state of California. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,49
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.080 - Authority to issue citations.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.080 - Authority to issue citations.
The director is authorized to issue and/or enter citations for violations of this title and applicable state laws. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,34
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.090 - Animal shelter hours of operations.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.090 - Animal shelter hours of operations.
The animal shelter shall be open for the redemption of impounded animals Wednesday through Saturday, except county- observed holidays. The hours of operation shall be conspicuously posted at the animal shelter. Hours of operation may be subject to change by the county administrative officer as set forth in Section 2.68.010 of this code. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,100
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.100 - Inspection of the animal shelter.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.100 - Inspection of the animal shelter.
The health officer shall cause the animal shelter to be inspected no less often than annually and at such times as directed by the board. The health officer shall report the conditions of the animal shelter to the director and the board within ten days of said inspection. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,64
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.110 - Authority to enter into contracts.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.110 - Authority to enter into contracts.
The director is authorized to enter into contracts with persons for impounding, transporting, and keeping of domestic animals within the county. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,190,Calaveras_County.pdf,39
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION,6.06.120 - Authority to conduct public education programs.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.06 - ADMINISTRATION | 6.06.120 - Authority to conduct public education programs.
The Director is authorized to conduct public education programs on responsible pet ownership. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,191,Calaveras_County.pdf,28
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 
Sections: ",Calaveras_County,191,Calaveras_County.pdf,3
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.010 - Impoundment by county personnel.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.010 - Impoundment by county personnel.
The director may take into custody and impound: A. Any animal kept or maintained contrary to the provisions of this title or any regulation adopted thereunder, or any California statute or federal statue. B. Any dog or livestock running at large in the County. C. Sick, injured, stray, or unwanted animals for which the owner or custodian cannot be found, or who is unwilling or unable to provide proper care. D. Animals quarantined for biting for which no other place of quarantine is acceptable to the health officer. E. Any nonexempt unlicensed dog. F. Any domestic animal that has been abandoned. G. Domestic animals requested to be impounded by a peace officer, public officer, or employee as defined in Penal Code Section 836.5. H. Domestic animals, at the director's discretion, that have been involved in an accident and that the owner is unable to care for. The director may forgive all impoundment fees for holding such animal(s) or may place such animal(s) in a foster home until the owner or authorized person is able to reclaim the animal (s). I. Any potentially dangerous or vicious dog as set forth in Chapter 6.12 of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,191,Calaveras_County.pdf,261
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.020 - Holding of impounded animals.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.020 - Holding of impounded animals.
A. Animals that are irremediably suffering from a serious illness or severe injury may be euthanized without being held for owner redemption or adoption. B. Newborn animals that need maternal care and have been impounded without their mothers may be euthanized without being held for owner redemption or adoption. C. Animals relinquished by the purported owner shall be held for two full business days, not including the day of impoundment. Such animals shall be available for owner redemption for the first day of the holding period, not including the day of impoundment, and shall be available for owner redemption or adoption for the remainder of the holding period. At the conclusion of the required holding period animals may be held longer, adopted, relinquished to a rescue organization or euthanized. D. Upon relinquishment of a dog or cat, the owner shall present sufficient identification to establish his/her ownership of said dog or cat and shall sign a statement that he/she is the lawful owner of said dog or cat. Upon relinquishment, the dog may be made available for immediate euthanasia if it has a history of vicious or dangerous behavior documented by the director. E. Notwithstanding subsection C of this section, kittens or puppies relinquished by the purported owner, or brought in by any other person with authority to relinquish them may immediately be made available for adoption. F. Unidentified, stray domestic animals that are impounded pursuant to this title shall be held for four business days, not including the day of impoundment. Such animals shall be held for owner redemption during the first three days of the holding period, not including the day of impoundment, and shall be available for owner redemption or adoption for the remainder of the holding period. G. Domestic animals that are impounded pursuant to this title whose owner can be identified shall be held for ten business days, not including the day of impoundment after mailing a notice of impoundment by United States mail to the last known address of the owner. After the conclusion of the holding period, animals may be held longer, adopted, relinquished to a rescue organization or euthanized. H. During the required holding periods and prior to adoption or euthanasia of any dog or cat impounded pursuant to this chapter, the director shall scan said dog or cat for a microchip and examine said dog or cat for the presence of any tattoo that identifies the owner and shall make reasonable efforts to contact the owner and notify him/her that their animal has been impounded and is available for redemption. When such microchips are discovered, the holding period specified in subsection G of this section shall apply. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,191,Calaveras_County.pdf,549
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.030 - Owner redemption of impounded animals.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.030 - Owner redemption of impounded animals.
A. The owner of an impounded animal may reclaim such animal at any time during the specified holding period and prior to other disposition of the animal(s) by paying all fees and charges as established by resolution of the board. B. In addition to paying the fees and charges specified in subsection A of this section, the owner of any nonspayed or unneutered dog or cat that is impounded shall be fined thirty-five dollars on the first occurrence, fifty dollars on the second occurrence and one hundred dollars on the third or subsequent occurrence in accordance with Sections 30804.7 and 31751.7 of the California Food and Agricultural Code. Any fines collected pursuant to this subdivision shall be deposited to the spay/neuter trust fund. C. Failure or refusal to pay any and all fees, charges, and fines associated with the impoundment of an animal shall constitute abandonment of said animals(s). The director may dispose of any animals so abandoned as described in this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,192,Calaveras_County.pdf,213
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.040 - Adoption of impounded animals.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.040 - Adoption of impounded animals.
A. At the conclusion of the required holding period for owner redemption, the director may make any impounded animal available for adoption. The adopting party shall enter into an adoption agreement with the director. No cat or dog over the age of three months shall be turned over to the adopting party without first being spayed or neutered unless a licensed veterinarian certifies that an animal is too sick or injured to be spayed or neutered or that it would otherwise be detrimental to the health of the cat or dog to be spayed or neutered. A spay/neuter deposit as established by resolution of the board shall be collected on all cats and dogs under the age of three months and those certified as too sick or injured at the time of adoption to be spayed or neutered. All spay/neuter fees and deposits shall be deposited to the spay/neuter trust fund, a non-interest bearing account. In the event a nursing female cat and her kittens or a nursing female dog and her puppies are adopted to one individual, only a single spay/neuter deposit shall be required. Except as otherwise provided, when a non-profit animal rescue or adoption organization enters into an agreement with the director for the release and adoption of sheltered animals, the requirement for spaying or neutering or posting of spay/neuter deposits prior to the release of such animals shall be waived pursuant to the terms and conditions of said agreement. B. All impounded dogs and cats will be implanted with a micro-chip upon the adoption of the dog or cat. Any impounded dog or cat released to a non-profit animal rescue or adoption organization will be implanted with a micro-chip. All fees for the implantation of the micro-chip will be included in the adoption fee. (Ord. 2748 § 1(part), 2004: Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 2948, § 1, 5-13-2008). ",Calaveras_County,192,Calaveras_County.pdf,404
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.050 - Placement of potentially adoptable animals in foster care.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.050 - Placement of potentially adoptable animals in foster care.
The director may place any impounded animal in foster care at the conclusion of the prescribed holding period for a period not to exceed six months while a permanent home for such animal(s) is being sought. All animals placed in foster care shall be relinquished to the director if not adopted within six months of placement. All animals adopted while in foster care shall be adopted pursuant to Section 6.08.040 of this title. All animals placed in foster care remain the property of the county until such time as they are adopted. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,193,Calaveras_County.pdf,119
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.060 - Adoption and foster placement agreements.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.060 - Adoption and foster placement agreements.
Any adoption or foster placement shall be made pursuant to an agreement developed by the director which shall contain terms and conditions as the director deems appropriate and shall further include a hold harmless clause protecting the county from liability that may arise from such adoption or foster placement. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,193,Calaveras_County.pdf,65
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.070 - Quarantine.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.070 - Quarantine.
A. When the director of the California Department of Health Services has declared the county a rabies area, the director is empowered to enter upon private premises where a biting or clinically suspected rabid animal is kept or has strayed. In all cases, rabid, or clinically suspected rabid animals, and if necessary to seize such animals for a period of ten days at a minimum. The impounding officer shall make reasonable effort to immediately notify the owner or custodian of the animal before it is impounded and the address of the facility where it will be taken. In lieu of impounding the animal, the health officer or director may, be serving written notice upon the owner, require the owner to quarantine the animal for such period and in a manner approved by the health officer. B. No person shall disobey any quarantine order issued pursuant to this section, or remove from its place of confinement, any animal under quarantine, without the permission of the health officer. Any person who violates the provisions of this section, or who violates an order of the health officer is guilty of a misdemeanor pursuant to Health and Safety Code section 120275. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,193,Calaveras_County.pdf,263
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.080 - Euthanasia of wild animals that bite or scratch humans required.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.080 - Euthanasia of wild animals that bite or scratch humans required.
Any wild animal, as defined in this title, that is susceptible to the rabies virus for which no anti-rabies vaccine has been approved by the Director of the California Department of Health Services, shall upon biting or scratching a human, be surrendered to the director for euthanasia and testing for the presence of the rabies virus. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,194,Calaveras_County.pdf,81
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT,6.08.090 - Duty to report.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.08 - IMPOUNDMENT | 6.08.090 - Duty to report.
Any person having knowledge of the location of an animal suspected of having rabies, or any person having been bitten or scratched by a warm-blooded mammal, or of any signs of unusual behavior in any animal under quarantine shall immediately report such facts to the health officer or director. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,194,Calaveras_County.pdf,70
