Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.10 - CONTROL AND NUISANCES,6.10.110 - Nuisance.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.10 - CONTROL AND NUISANCES | 6.10.110 - Nuisance.
A. No person shall keep, maintain or permit either willfully or through failure to exercise proper control, on any lot, parcel of land, or premises under his/her control, any animal(s), including livestock, which disturbs the peace and comfort of the inhabitants of the neighborhood, or interferes with the reasonable and comfortable enjoyment of life or property. No summons and complaint shall be issued for any violation of this section unless there are at least two or more complaining witnesses from separate households who have signed such complaint. In appropriate cases, as determined by the director of the department of animal services or their designee, any animal control officer or police officer who has personally investigated the complaint of a single complainant, and observed problem behavior or nuisance, may be the second complaining witness. Conditions constituting a nuisance under this section include: 1. Excessive dust; 2. Excessive noise; 3. Excessive odors; 4. Vectors; 5. Threat to health. B. Any dog which has been allowed or permitted to persistently and chronically violate this section, including the conditions set forth in subsection A, as demonstrated by one or more convictions for violating this section, and the receipt of subsequent complaints from more than one household, is declared to be a public nuisance and may be impounded upon compliance with the procedures outlined in subsections C through I. C. Whenever any chronic barking dog nuisance as defined in subsection B of this section is found on any premises within the jurisdiction of the county, a written notice shall be given to the owner, possessor or keeper of the dog, or to the owner, occupant, person in possession, person in charge or person in control of the premises where the dog is located, or a written notice shall be posted at such premises when none of the above people can be found at the premises. Such notice shall be signed by the director of the animal services or his or her authorized representative and shall give the person or persons to whom it is directed no less than seventy-two hours (three days) nor more than one hundred twenty hours (five days) to abate the chronic barking dog nuisance. Such notice shall also state that the dog may be impounded if the barking dog nuisance is not abated. D. If, after the time given to comply with the notice has passed, the barking dog nuisance has not been abated, the director of the animal services or designee may: summarily abate the barking dog nuisance by impounding the barking dog; assess the costs of such abatement against the owner, possessor or keeper of the dog, or to the owner, occupant, person in possession, person in charge or person in control of the premises where the dog is located, to be collected by suit or otherwise; and issue a citation for the violation of this section. The impoundment shall continue until the resolution of the citation issued in conjunction with the impoundment or, until the director or a hearing officer has conducted the administrative hearing described in this section and determined that the dog does not constitute a barking dog nuisance and should be released. E. At the time any dog is impounded as a barking dog nuisance, the director or their designee shall serve a notice on the owner, possessor or keeper of the dog, or to the owner, occupant, person in possession, person in charge or person in control of the premises where the dog is located; or a written notice shall be posted at such premises when none of the above people can be found at the premises. Such notice shall be signed by the director of the animal services or his or her authorized representative. Such notice shall state that the dog has been impounded as a chronic barking dog nuisance under this section; that the owners, possessors, and keepers of the dog are entitled to a hearing to contest the impoundment; that to obtain such a hearing, the owner, possessor, or keeper must submit a written petition for release of the dog, containing the petitioner's name and address, including mailing address, and the reason the dog should not be classified as a chronic barking dog nuisance; and that this petition must be filed with the director within seven business days of the impoundment. If the last day of this seven-day period falls on a non business day or holiday, the time for filing the petition shall be extended to the next regular business day. F. When a dog has been impounded pursuant to this section, and the owner, possessor or keeper of such dog disputes the classification of such dog as a chronic barking dog nuisance, the owner, possessor or keeper of such dog may file a written petition for a hearing concerning such classification with the director no later than seven business days after impoundment. If the last day of this seven-day period falls on a non business day or holiday, the time for filing the petition shall be extended to the next regular business day. Such petition shall include the petitioner's name and address, including mailing address and the reason the petitioner believes the dog should not be classified as a chronic barking dog nuisance. The petition shall be set for a hearing to be held on a date no more than thirty days after the date the petition is filed. The director, or the director's designee, shall issue a notice of the hearing date by mailing a copy to the petitioner's address no later than ten days prior to the date of the hearing. The director, or the director's designee, shall post a public notice of the hearing for a minimum of two weeks prior to the hearing date. Where the owners, possessors, or keepers of the dog fail to file a written petition with the director within seven days of the impoundment, excluding non business days and holidays, they shall be deemed to have waived their right to a hearing to contest the classification of the dog as a chronic barking dog nuisance. G. The hearing on the chronic barking dog classification shall be held before the director or a hearing officer designated by the director. The sole issue at the hearing shall be whether the dog constitutes a chronic barking dog nuisance as defined in subsection B of this section. The hearing shall not address the sufficiency of abatement or any other issues. H. If the hearing officer determines the dog does constitute a chronic barking dog nuisance as defined in subsection B of this section, the hearing officer shall make a determination to the disposition of the offending dog and remand custody of the offending dog to the director of animal services for re-homing or humane destruction. The owners, possessors, or keepers of the dog shall be responsible for all cost associated with the impoundment and housing of the animal until the time the animal is remanded to the custody of the director. I. This section shall not apply to agricultural activities, operations, or facilities, or appurtenances thereof that are exempt as set forth in California Civil Code section 3482.5. J. This section shall not apply to agricultural processing activities, operations, facility, or appurtenances thereof that are exempt as set forth in California Civil Code section 3482.6. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,196,Calaveras_County.pdf,1495
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.10 - CONTROL AND NUISANCES,6.10.120 - Disposal of dead animals.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.10 - CONTROL AND NUISANCES | 6.10.120 - Disposal of dead animals.
The owner of any animal which dies shall dispose of the carcass of such animal in a sanitary manner as prescribed by the director within seventy-two hours after the owner has knowledge of the animal's death. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,198,Calaveras_County.pdf,54
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.10 - CONTROL AND NUISANCES,6.10.130 - Display and o␀ering animals in public prohibited.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.10 - CONTROL AND NUISANCES | 6.10.130 - Display and o␀ering animals in public prohibited.
Except as provided herein, the placing or displaying on any public property in Calaveras County, of any dog, cat, puppy, kitten, or other animal for the purpose of offering to sell, give away, or otherwise dispose of said animal is prohibited. This section shall not apply to the display or offering of animals for adoption or sale from the animal shelter, when such display or offering is performed by animal services department personnel, or humane organizations acting under the auspices of the animal services department or in conjunction with said department. (Ord. 2901 § 1, 2006). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,198,Calaveras_County.pdf,142
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 
Sections: ",Calaveras_County,198,Calaveras_County.pdf,3
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.010 - Purpose—Exemptions.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.010 - Purpose—Exemptions.
The purpose of this chapter is to implement a program for the control of potentially dangerous and vicious dogs pursuant to and consistent with Chapter 9 (commencing with Section 31601) of Division 14 of the Food and Agricultural Code. This chapter does not apply to licensed kennels, humane society shelters, the county animal shelter, veterinarians, or to dogs while utilized by any police department or any law enforcement officer in the performance of police work. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,198,Calaveras_County.pdf,104
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.020 - Filing petition with superior court—Hearing.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.020 - Filing petition with superior court—Hearing.
If after investigation, it is determined that there exists probable cause to believe that a dog is potentially dangerous or vicious, the director shall petition the superior court for a hearing for the purpose of determining whether or not the dog in question should be declared potentially dangerous or vicious. Whenever possible, any complaint received from a member of the public which serves as the evidentiary basis for the director to find probable cause shall be sworn to and verified by the complainant and shall be attached to the petition. The owner of the dog shall be notified that a hearing will be held by the superior court at which time such owner may present evidence as to why the dog should not be declared potentially dangerous or vicious. The owner of the dog shall be served with notice of the hearing and a copy of the petition, either personally or by first-class mail with return receipt requested. The hearing shall be held promptly within no less than five working days nor more than ten working days after service of notice upon the owner of the dog. The hearing shall be open to the public. The court may admit into evidence all relevant evidence, including incident reports and the affidavits of witnesses, limit the scope of discovery, and may shorten the time to produce records or witnesses. A jury shall not be available. The court may find, upon preponderance of the evidence, that the dog is potentially dangerous or vicious and make other orders authorized by this chapter and state law. The court may decide all issues for or against the owner of the dog even if such owner fails to appear at the hearing. (Ord. 2745 § 1(part), 2004: Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,198,Calaveras_County.pdf,340
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.030 - Notice of decision by superior court—Appeal to superior court.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.030 - Notice of decision by superior court—Appeal to superior court.
A. After the hearing conducted pursuant to Section 6.12.020, the owner of the dog shall be notified in writing of the determination and orders issued by the court, either personally or by first-class mail, postage prepaid, by the court. If a determination is made that the dog is potentially dangerous or vicious, the owner of the dog shall comply with this chapter and state law in accordance with a time schedule established by the director, but in no case more than thirty days after the date of the determination is mailed to such owner. If the director or such owner may, within five days of the receipt of the notice of determination, appeal the decision to the appeals department of the superior court. The fee for filing an appeal shall be as set forth in subdivision (a) of Food and Agricultural Code Section 31622 or its successor, payable to the county clerk. The director or the owner of the dog shall serve personally or by first-class mail, postage prepaid, notice of the appeal upon the other party. B. The superior court shall conduct a hearing de novo, without a jury, and make its own determination as to potential danger and viciousness and make other orders authorized by this chapter and state law, based upon the evidence presented. The hearing shall be conducted in the same manner and within the time periods set forth in Section 6.12.020 and subsection (A) of this section. The court may admit all relevant evidence, including incident reports and affidavits of witnesses, limit the scope of discovery, and may shorten the time to produce records or witnesses. The issue shall be decided upon the preponderance of the evidence. If the court rules the dog to be potentially dangerous or vicious, the court may establish a time schedule to ensure compliance with this chapter and state law, but in no case more than thirty days subsequent to the date of the court's determination or thirty-five days if the service of the judgment is by first-class mail. The court may decide all issues for or against the owner of the dog even if such owner fails to appear at the hearing. The determination of the court shall be final and conclusive upon all parties. (Ord. 2745 § 1(part), 2004: Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,199,Calaveras_County.pdf,463
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.040 - Impoundment of dog pending hearings.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.040 - Impoundment of dog pending hearings.
A. If upon investigation it is determined by the director that probable cause exists to believe a dog is potentially dangerous or vicious and poses an immediate threat to public safety, then the director may seize and impound the dog pending the hearings to be held pursuant to this chapter. The owner of the dog shall be liable to the office of animal control for the costs and expenses of keeping the dog, if the dog is later adjudicated potentially dangerous or vicious. B. When a dog has been impounded pursuant to subsection A of this section and it is not contrary to public safety, the director shall permit the dog to be confined at the owner's expense in a commercial kennel or veterinary facility approved by the director. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,199,Calaveras_County.pdf,156
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.050 - Mitigating circumstances.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.050 - Mitigating circumstances.
A. No dog may be declared potentially dangerous or vicious if any injury or damage is sustained by a person who at the time the injury or damage was sustained, was committing a willful trespass or other tort upon premises occupied by the owner of the dog, or was teasing, tormenting, abusing or assaulting the dog, or was committing or attempting to commit a crime. No dog may be declared potentially dangerous or vicious if the dog was protecting or defending a person within the immediate vicinity of the dog from an unjustified attack or assault. No dog may be declared potentially dangerous or vicious if an injury or damage was sustained by a domestic animal which at the time the injury or damage was sustained was teasing, tormenting, abusing or assaulting the dog. B. No dog may be declared potentially dangerous or vicious if the injury or damage to a domestic animal was sustained while the dog was working as a hunting dog, herding dog, or predator control dog on property of, or under the control of, its owner, and the damage or injury was to a species or type of domestic animal appropriate to the work of the dog. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,199,Calaveras_County.pdf,238
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.060 - Disposition of potentially dangerous dogs.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.060 - Disposition of potentially dangerous dogs.
A. A dog determined to be a potentially dangerous dog, either after the owner of the dog has agreed to the designation or the court has determined the designation applies to the dog, shall be placed on a list of potentially dangerous dogs by the director and shall be maintained by the owner as follows: 1. A potentially dangerous dog shall be properly licensed and vaccinated. The director shall include the potentially dangerous designation in the registration records of the dog, and shall charge a potentially dangerous dog fee, the amount of which shall be established by resolution of the board in addition to the required license fee. In addition, a potentially dangerous dog shall be micro-chipped at the owner's expense. The owner is required to provide the chip number to animal services and provide proof the chip number has been registered with the micro-chip company. An animal services officer has the right to scan the dog in question to verify the implantation of a micro- chip and to confirm the micro-chip number provided by the owner matches the scanned micro-chip implanted in the potentially dangerous dog. 2. Upon the issuance of a notice of determination that a dog is potentially dangerous, as a condition of allowing the owner to take or retain custody of the dog, the director may require the owner to provide proof of general liability insurance for injury or death to any person or animal in an amount of not less than one million dollars, nor more than five million dollars. Said insurance shall remain in full force and effect for as long as the owner maintains custody of the potentially dangerous dog or until the dog is removed from the list of potentially dangerous dogs as provided in Subsection B. of this section. 3. A potentially dangerous dog, while on the owner's premises, shall at all times be kept indoors, or in a secure enclosure. A potentially dangerous dog may be off the owner's premises only if it is restrained by a substantial leash not exceeding six feet in length and it is under the control of a responsible adult. 4. If a potentially dangerous dog dies, or is sold, transferred, or permanently removed from the county, the owner shall notify the director of the changed conditions and new location of the dog in writing within two working days after such change. B. If there are not additional instances of the behavior described under potentially dangerous dog in Section 6.04.030 of this title within a thirty-six-month period from the date of designation as a potentially dangerous dog, the dog shall be removed from the list of potentially dangerous dogs by the director. The dog may, but is not required to be, removed from the list of potentially dangerous dogs prior to the expiration of the thirty-six month period if the owner of the dog demonstrates to the satisfaction of the director that changes in circumstances or measures taken by such owner, such as training of the dog, have mitigated the risk to public safety. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 2949, § 1, 5-13-2008). ",Calaveras_County,200,Calaveras_County.pdf,611
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.070 - Disposition of vicious dogs.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.070 - Disposition of vicious dogs.
A. A dog determined to be a vicious dog may be humanely destroyed by the director when it is found, after proceedings conducted pursuant to this chapter, that the release of the dog would create a significant threat to the public health, safety and welfare. B. If it is determined that a dog found to be vicious shall not be destroyed, the court shall impose conditions upon the ownership of the dog that protects the public's health, safety, and welfare, including reserving jurisdiction to order destruction of the dog upon any further violation of this chapter or state law. Any enclosure that is required as a condition of ownership shall be a secure enclosure. A vicious dog shall be properly licensed and vaccinated. The director shall include the vicious designation in the registration records of the dog, and shall charge a vicious dog fee, the amount of which shall be established by resolution of the board, in addition to the required license fee. Furthermore, a vicious dog shall be micro-chipped at the owner's expense. The owner is required to provide the chip number to animal services and provide proof the chip number has been registered with the micro-chip company. An animal services officer has the right to scan the dog in question to verify the implantation of a micro-chip and to confirm the micro-chip number provided by the owner matches the scanned micro-chip implanted in the vicious dog. C. Upon the issuance of notice of determination that a dog is found to be vicious, as a condition of allowing the owner to take or retain custody of the dog, the director may require the owner to provide proof of general liability insurance for injury or death to any person or animal in an amount of not less than one million dollars, nor more than five million dollars. Said insurance shall remain in full force and effect for as long as the owner maintains custody of the vicious dog. D. No dog determined to be vicious shall be sold, transferred or permanently removed from the county without the written approval of the director and the written approval of the regulating agency of the receiving jurisdiction if applicable. The owner shall notify the director of the changed conditions and new location of the dog in writing within two business days after such change occurs. E. The owner of a dog determined to be vicious shall notify the director within two business days of the death of such dog. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 2950, § 1, 5-13-2008). ",Calaveras_County,200,Calaveras_County.pdf,499
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS,6.12.080 - Restrictions on further ownership of dogs.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.12 - POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS AND VICIOUS DOGS | 6.12.080 - Restrictions on further ownership of dogs.
The owner of a dog determined to be a vicious dog shall be prohibited from owning, possessing, controlling or having custody of any dog for a period of three years, when it is found, after proceedings conducted pursuant to this chapter, that ownership or possession of a dog by that person would create a significant threat to the public health, safety, and welfare. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,201,Calaveras_County.pdf,85
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 
Sections: Footnotes: --- (2) --- State Law reference— For statutory provisions on the licensing and regulation of dogs by counties, see Gov. Code § 38792 and Food and Agriculture Code § 30651 et seq.; for provisions on rabies control, see Health and Safety Code § 121.575 et seq. ",Calaveras_County,201,Calaveras_County.pdf,68
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.010 - Dog licensing.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.010 - Dog licensing.
The director shall maintain and carry out a system for the issuance, renewal, and recording of dog licenses in accordance with this title. Dog licenses are issued for a period of one, two, or three years and renewed on the anniversary date of the rabies vaccination at the end of the one, two, or three-year licensing period. License tags are issued for the life of the dog except that duplicate tags may be issued to replace lost, worn, or damaged tags. License tags shall be of durable material, bear the stamped words ""Calaveras County,"" and a unique number. Licensing fees may be adopted and increased by the board of supervisors pursuant to Food and Agricultural Code 30804. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 2947, § 1, 5-13-2008; Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) Editor's note— Ord. No. 2947, § 1, adopted May 13, 2008, changed the title of Section 6.14.010 from dog license to dog licensing. ",Calaveras_County,201,Calaveras_County.pdf,237
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.020 - Dog license—Required.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.020 - Dog license—Required.
A. Every person owning or having custody of any dog four months of age or older shall procure a county dog license for the dog. Such license shall be procured within thirty days after the date on which it becomes due. The following are exceptions to the requirement to license: 1. Dogs maintained in a licensed kennel, provided the dog is owned by the owner or operator of the kennel; 2. Dogs used in police work by a law enforcement official, provided the dog is registered with the director; 3. Service dogs as defined under federal and state law, or being trained for such use which shall be issued a special tag in accordance with Section 30850 and described in Section 30852 of the Food and Agriculture Code. B. No dog shall be licensed without proof of approved rabies vaccination. No license may expire later than the expiration date of the rabies vaccination. An owner may purchase a license upon showing proof of a valid rabies vaccination and, upon payment of the fee established by resolution of the board. C. Owners of dogs establishing residency in Calaveras County will be required to procure a Calaveras County dog license within thirty days of establishing that residency. If the dog(s) are currently licensed and currently vaccinated for rabies in the previous county of residence, with proof of said vaccination and licensing, the director may honor that licensing until the next anniversary date of the rabies vaccination, at which time the owner will be required to procure a Calaveras County dog license. D. First violation of this section is an infraction. If the dog owner does not license the dog within thirty days after the first conviction of this section, the dog owner is in violation of this section and guilty of a misdemeanor or an infraction. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,202,Calaveras_County.pdf,392
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.030 - Wearing of dog license tag required.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.030 - Wearing of dog license tag required.
Each dog required to be licensed shall, at all times, wear the current license tag assigned to that dog. Lost license tags may be replaced by applying for a duplicate tag from the director. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,202,Calaveras_County.pdf,52
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.040 - Dog license—Renewal.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.040 - Dog license—Renewal.
A. Licenses not purchased or renewed within thirty days after expiration, or the date on which they become due, shall be considered delinquent and a late fee, as determined by resolution of the board, shall be added to the cost of the new license. If the license for a single dog is delinquent for two or more years, the back license fees will apply to bring that license current. With proof of transfer of ownership, the new owner of a delinquent dog will not be held liable for the past license fees or delinquent fees. B. At the director's discretion, the director may hold an amnesty period, not exceeding sixty days, every three or five years from the date of the last amnesty period to encourage Calaveras County citizens to license their dogs who might otherwise not do so due to the penalties. During the amnesty period, licensing can be brought current without incurring the additional fees or the late fee described in subsection A of this section. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). (Ord. No. 3009, § 1, 5-22-2012) ",Calaveras_County,202,Calaveras_County.pdf,233
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.050 - Dog license—Transfer of ownership.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.050 - Dog license—Transfer of ownership.
Upon the transfer of ownership of any licensed dog, the license may be transferred to the new owner provided that the Director is notified in writing within fifteen days of such transfer of ownership and the name and address of the new owner is provided. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,203,Calaveras_County.pdf,61
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.060 - Restrictions on keeping of animals capable of transmitting rabies.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.060 - Restrictions on keeping of animals capable of transmitting rabies.
A. It shall be unlawful for any person to own, keep, harbor or possess within the county any animal of the family Canidae capable of transmitting the rabies virus unless such animal can be immunized with a rabies vaccine approved by the State Department of Health Services, except that wild animals may be kept with a valid permit issued by the Department of Fish and Game at an approved facility. This exception shall not apply to hybrids of such species. B. All animals kept in accordance with this section shall comply with the provisions of the latest version of Manual No. 671 and all subsequent versions issued by the California Department of Fish and Game, which is adopted and incorporated herein by reference. Such animals shall not be sold, offered for sale, adopted or given away except to another properly licensed facility. C. The director may enforce all provisions of said manual relating to Humane Care and Treatment of Wild Animals and Minimum Facility and Caging Standards for Wild Animals Housed at Permanent Facilities which for the purposes of this section shall include rescue facilities. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,203,Calaveras_County.pdf,223
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.070 - Dog vaccination required.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.070 - Dog vaccination required.
Every person owning or harboring a dog four months of age or older, for fifteen days or more, shall have such a dog vaccinated against rabies by a licensed veterinarian with a vaccine approved by the California Department of Health, unless such dog is currently vaccinated. By obtaining an anti-rabies deferment from a licensed veterinarian, upon approval of the health officer, dogs that are ill may be given temporary deferment from rabies vaccination. Old age of the dog, however, shall not be a basis for such deferment. Such a deferred dog shall be vaccinated within fifteen days from the conclusion of the deferment period. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,203,Calaveras_County.pdf,138
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.080 - Proof of vaccination.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.080 - Proof of vaccination.
No person who owns or harbors any dog shall fail or refuse to exhibit his copy of the rabies vaccination form, anti-rabies inoculation deferment form or health certificate upon demand by any person charged with the enforcement of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,203,Calaveras_County.pdf,62
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.14.090 - Vaccination reports.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.14.090 - Vaccination reports.
A. Any person who performs any rabies vaccination on any dog, whether as a clinic authorized by the director or as a licensed veterinarian shall report such vaccination, the name and address of the owner of such animal, and the date of such vaccination to the director. Such reports shall be made in writing and filed with the director by the fifteenth day of each month for all vaccinations administered during the preceding month. B. It shall also be the duty of any licensed veterinarian practicing veterinary medicine in the county to report the name and address of the owner of any dog examined or treated by said veterinarian for any other reason to the director in the same manner as provided in subsection a of this section. C. This section shall become inoperative at such time as the county is no longer declared a rabies endemic area by the California Department of Health Services. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). Chapter 6.16. - ANIMAL PERMITS Sections: ",Calaveras_County,203,Calaveras_County.pdf,197
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.010 - Animal permits required.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.010 - Animal permits required.
Every person who is the owner of four or more dogs or five or more cats over the age of four months which are not subject to a kennel license pursuant to the provisions of Chapter 6.18 of this title shall obtain a permit from the director to keep such animals. Upon denial or revocation of an animal permit, or upon notice from the director, the owner shall reduce the number of dogs and/or cats they own to no more than three dogs or no more than four cats within thirty days after notice of denial or revocation by the director pursuant to Section 6.04.100 of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,204,Calaveras_County.pdf,138
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.020 - Types of animal permits.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.020 - Types of animal permits.
There shall be three types of animal permits which the director may issue: A. Interim animal permit; B. Ranch dog permit; and C. Foster care permit. (Ord. 2745 § 1(part), 2004: Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,204,Calaveras_County.pdf,62
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.030 - Interim animal permits.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.030 - Interim animal permits.
The director may issue interim animal permits to persons who own more than three dogs or more than four cats provided all of the following conditions are met: A. All dogs over the age of four months are individually licensed and have current rabies vaccinations. B. Dogs and cats subject to an interim animal permit shall be individually identified on the original application and on all subsequent applications for renewal. C. Dogs and cats which are subject to an interim animal permit shall be kept in such a manner as not to become a nuisance to surrounding and nearby neighbors. D. No new or additional dogs or cats shall be added to an interim animal permit. E. The applicant shall spay or neuter all dogs and all cats that are subject to an interim animal permit. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,204,Calaveras_County.pdf,164
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.040 - Ranch dog permits.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.040 - Ranch dog permits.
The director may issue ranch dog permits to persons who own more than three dogs and who can demonstrate that said dogs are necessary to pursue a legitimate livestock production endeavor provided all of the following conditions are met: A. All dogs over the age of four months are individually licensed and have current rabies vaccinations. B. Dogs subject to a ranch dog permit shall be identified on the original application and on all subsequent applications for renewal. C. Dogs which are subject to a ranch dog permit shall be kept in such a manner as not to become a nuisance to surrounding and nearby neighbors. D. The holder of a ranch dog permit shall notify the director within ten days of the date of acquiring any new or additional dogs subject to said permit. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,205,Calaveras_County.pdf,159
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.045 - Foster care permits.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.045 - Foster care permits.
The director may issue foster care permits to persons who own three dogs of their own and who wish to foster additional dogs on a temporary basis for a non-profit animal rescue or adoption organization that has entered into an agreement with the director for the release of sheltered animals provided that all of the following conditions are met: A. All dogs over the age of four months that are owned by the foster care giver are individually licensed and have current rabies vaccinations. B. Foster care permits shall be limited to no more than two additional dogs, not to exceed a total of five dogs, over the age of four months, at any time. C. Dogs subject to a foster care permit shall not be kept for a period of more than six months at the same residence unless an extension is requested by the permittee and granted by the director. D. Dogs which are subject to a foster care permit shall be kept in such a manner as to not become a nuisance to surrounding and nearby neighbors. (Ord. 2748 § 1(part), 2004). ",Calaveras_County,205,Calaveras_County.pdf,212
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.050 - Expiration of animal permits.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.050 - Expiration of animal permits.
All animal permits shall expire on the last day of the twelfth month from the date of issuance and shall become delinquent if not renewed within thirty days of said expiration. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,205,Calaveras_County.pdf,49
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.060 - Animal permits nontransferable.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.060 - Animal permits nontransferable.
Animal permits issued pursuant to this chapter are nontransferable as to the owner and location of the premises for which they are issued. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,205,Calaveras_County.pdf,40
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.070 - Inspection of premises subject to an animal permit.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.070 - Inspection of premises subject to an animal permit.
The director shall, prior to the issuance of an animal permit, inspect the premises where such animals are to be kept to insure compliance with the provisions of this chapter. The director may periodically inspect the premises for which an animal permit has been issued or is in the process of being renewed, to insure compliance with the provisions of this chapter and at such times as complaints are received about such permitted premises. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,205,Calaveras_County.pdf,93
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES,6.16.080 - Denial or revocation of an animal permit.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.14 - DOG LICENSES | 6.16.080 - Denial or revocation of an animal permit.
The director may, after investigation, deny or revoke an animal permit for failure to comply with the provisions of this chapter. Such denial or revocation shall be made subject to Section 6.04.100 and is subject to appeal in accordance with Section 6.04.110 of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,206,Calaveras_County.pdf,74
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 
Sections: ",Calaveras_County,206,Calaveras_County.pdf,3
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.010 - Kennel license required.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.010 - Kennel license required.
Every person who is the owner of four or more dogs or five or more cats which are not subject to an animal permit, as provided for in Chapter 6.16 of this title, shall obtain a kennel license from the director or reduce the number of dogs and/or cats they own to no more than three individually licensed dogs and/or four cats within thirty days of being denied such license by the director. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,206,Calaveras_County.pdf,96
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.020 - Types of kennel licenses.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.020 - Types of kennel licenses.
There shall be two types of kennel licenses which the director may issue. A. Private kennel license; B. Commercial kennel license. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,206,Calaveras_County.pdf,43
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.030 - Private kennel license.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.030 - Private kennel license.
The director may issue a private kennel license to persons keeping dogs or cats intended for exhibition in conformation, field trials, or other activities such as obedience training, hunting, herding, tracking, rescue, or service work, or which are bred or raised for such purposes, provided all of the following conditions and the requirements contained in Section 6.18.050 of this chapter are met. A. The land on which a private kennel is located is properly zoned for such use in Title 17 of this code. B. Private kennel licenses shall be restricted as to the maximum number of dogs and/or cats over the age of four months on the basis of parcel size: 1. 5.00-9.99 acre parcels, no more than a total of ten dogs and/or cats. 2. 10.00-14.99 acre parcels, no more than a total of fifteen dogs and/or cats. 3. 15.00 acre and larger parcels, no more than a total of twenty dogs and/or cats. C. Breeding shall be limited to no more than two specific breeds. There is, however, no limit on the number of breeds tha kept at a private kennel. D. Breeding at an appropriate kennel shall be restricted to no more than four litters of puppies or kittens within a two- year period. For the purposes of this section, a litter shall be a minimum of three live puppies or kittens at the age of six weeks. E. Private kennels shall have sufficient animal enclosures or runs to isolate females in heat from males in order to control breeding. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,206,Calaveras_County.pdf,346
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.040 - Commercial kennel license.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.040 - Commercial kennel license.
The director may issue a commercial kennel license to persons keeping dogs or cats where the primary purpose of such activity is for financial gain. Commercial kennels may engage in all activities allowed and authorized under a private kennel, commercial boarding and breeding for the purpose of selling such offspring provided all of the following conditions and the requirements contained in Section 6.18.050 of this chapter are met. A. The land on which a commercial kennel is located is properly zoned for such use as specified in Title 17 of this code. B. No commercial kennel shall be operated and no animals shall be housed therein until such time as the facility has been deemed complete by the county building official and a license has been issued by the director. C. All enclosures and animal runs shall be constructed of nonabsorbent materials and sloped in such a manner as to facilitate drainage into an approved sewer or septage system. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,207,Calaveras_County.pdf,200
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.050 - Requirements for all kennels.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.050 - Requirements for all kennels.
Every private and commercial kennel shall comply with the following: A. Every dog over the age of four months, subject to a kennel license, shall have a current rabies vaccination and such records shall be made available to the director upon request. B. No dog over the age of four months shall be boarded at any licensed kennel unless the owner of such dog provides proof of current rabies vaccination. The owner of the kennel shall retain a copy of such rabies vaccination certificates and make them available to the director upon request. C. All dogs and cats subject to a kennel license shall be kept in such a manner as not to become a nuisance to surrounding and nearby neighbors. D. All kennel facilities shall be structurally sound and kept in good repair at all times for the health and well being of the animals housed therein, restrict entry by unauthorized persons or unwanted animals, and prevent the escape of kenneled animals. E. All kennel facilities including, but not limited to, buildings, enclosures, and runs shall be maintained in a clean and sanitary manner. All animal waste shall be removed and disposed of on a daily basis. F. All licensed kennels shall, at a minimum, conform to the latest version of the Animal Welfare Act and 9CFR Subpart A-Specifications for the Humane Holding, Care, Treatment, and Transportation of Dogs and Cats, or local standards, whichever is more restrictive. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,207,Calaveras_County.pdf,306
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.060 - Application for kennel license.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.060 - Application for kennel license.
Application for a kennel license shall be made in writing to the director by the owner of the kennel to be licensed. Such application shall be on a form approved by the director and shall be accompanied by a license fee in the amount established by resolution of the board. Such license fee shall be in lieu of any license fees required in Section 6.14.020 of this title. The applicant shall obtain approval for the kennel from all related departments including, but not limited to, zoning, building permits, business license, and fictitious business name prior to submitting an application for a new kennel to the director. If the owner of a kennel fails to make application for a kennel license or renewal of a kennel license within thirty days after receipt of notice from the director to obtain or renew a kennel license, the owner shall pay a penalty for late licensing in an amount established by resolution of the board. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,207,Calaveras_County.pdf,200
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.070 - Expiration of kennel license.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.070 - Expiration of kennel license.
All kennel licenses shall expire on the last day of the twelfth month from the date of issuance and shall become delinquent if not renewed within thirty days of said expiration. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,208,Calaveras_County.pdf,50
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.080 - Keeping of spayed or neutered dogs and cats.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.080 - Keeping of spayed or neutered dogs and cats.
The owner of a kennel may keep spayed or neutered dogs and cats without individually licensing said animals provided the maximum number of animals for which the licenses was issued is not exceeded. The owner of a kennel may keep three spayed or neutered dogs over the age of four months in addition to the maximum number of dogs allowed under the kennel license, provided such dogs are individually licensed in accordance with Section 6.14.020 and currently vaccinated for rabies in accordance with Section 6.14.070 of this title. The owner of a kennel may keep four spayed or neutered cats over the age of four months in addition to the maximum number of cats allowed under the kennel license. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,208,Calaveras_County.pdf,159
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.090 - Kennel license transferable.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.090 - Kennel license transferable.
Kennel licenses issued pursuant to this chapter shall be transferable to new owners or leasees of the real property for which a license has been issued provided the zoning, parcel size, and maximum number of animals remains the same. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,208,Calaveras_County.pdf,59
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.100 - Inspection of premises subject to kennel licenses.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.100 - Inspection of premises subject to kennel licenses.
The director shall, prior to the issuance of a new kennel license and prior to the renewal of an existing kennel license, inspect the premises to insure compliance with the provisions of this chapter. The director may, periodically, inspect licensed kennels to insure compliance with the provisions of this chapter at any reasonable hour of the day. The director shall notify the owner of the kennel, in writing, of any violations observed at the time of inspection and provide the owner a reasonable amount of time, not to exceed thirty days to make any necessary corrections. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,208,Calaveras_County.pdf,124
Title 6 - ANIMALS,Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES,6.18.110 - Denial or revocation of kennel license.,"Calaveras_County | Title 6 - ANIMALS | Chapter 6.18 - KENNEL LICENSES | 6.18.110 - Denial or revocation of kennel license.
The director may, after investigation, deny or revoke a kennel license for failure to comply with the provisions of this chapter. Such denial or revocation shall be made subject to Section 6.04.100 and is subject to appeal in accordance with Section 6.04.110 of this title. (Ord. 2641 (part), 2001). ",Calaveras_County,208,Calaveras_County.pdf,75
