A. The following minimum road surface material requirements shall be applicable for all roads set forth in this chapter. 1. The following minimum structural section shall be applicable for all public roads: Table VI MINIMUM STRUCTURAL SECTION Road Class Road Base (1) Asphalt Concrete Tra␀c Index (2) Major Collector/ Through 6″ 2″ 6.0 Minor Collector/ 6″ 2″ 5.0 Connector Local/ Residential 4″ 2″ 4.5 Commercial/ Industrial 6″ 2″ 7.0 (1) Minimum requirement is based on Class 2 aggregate base (A.B.) (2) As specified in county traffic index charts contained in the county standard details. 2. The following minimum structural sections shall be applicable to all private roads: Table VII PRIVATE ROADS: SURFACE REQUIREMENTS Smallest lot Under 3,000′ Elevation Over or Equal to 3,000′ Elevation Under 20.1 acres Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and 2″ A.C. Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and 2″ A.C. 20.1 to 39.9 acres <12% road grade Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and 2″ A.C. 20.1 to 39.9 acres ≥12% road grade Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and single chip Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and 2"" A.C. seal over oil penetration 40 to 160 acres, or ¼ - ¼ section to Graded earth roadbed Graded earth roadbed ¼ section Over 160 acres or >¼ section No requirements No requirements Cul-de-sac ≥5 ac (3) Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and 2″ A.C. Minimum Service Road >5 acres Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 Min. 4″ A.B. Class 2 and 2″ A.C. Emergency Access <10% road grade Graded roadbed 4″ A.B. Class 2 Emergency Access >10% road grade 4″ A.B. Class 2 4″ A.B. Class 2 (3) ;hg;Minimum 2″ A.C. overlay required if cul-de-sac serves more than four parcels, cumulatively. B. Structural sections for all asphalt surfaced roads required by this chapter shall be designed in accordance with the Highway Design Manual for the minimum traffic indexes set forth above and ""R"" value test data provided by an approved soils testing laboratory. C. Community Area Curb, Gutter and Sidewalk Requirements. 1. Sidewalks, curbs, and gutters are required on all community roads where minimum residential lot size is twenty thousand square feet or less as indicated in Table III of Section 12.02.160 and Table V of Section 12.02.170. Alternate pathway systems and engineered drainage may be allowed in place of sidewalks and curbs and gutters on a case- by-case basis as approved by the director. 2. Sidewalks, curbs, and gutters are required for all commercial developments in community centers, community plan areas, and specific plan areas as indicated in Table II of Section 12.02.160 and Table IV of Section 12.02.170. 3. Sidewalks, curbs, and gutters in industrial developments may be required on a case-by-case basis by the director. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,342,Calaveras_County.pdf,775
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.190 - General design standards.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.190 - General design standards.
A. The design standards provide the minimum standards for the design, construction and alterations for all streets, roadways, drainage, utility placement, and all appurtenances thereto. The design standards shall consist of the applicable provisions in the Highway Design Manual, the standard plans and this chapter. B. The director, at his discretion, may approve or require modifications to the minimum standards for a particular development whenever it appears necessary, reasonable and proper. Modifications will not be allowed unless the request is accompanied by written justification and certification by a licensed engineer that traffic safety is not compromised. C. The director shall be the final authority on all questions which may arise as to the interpretation of the design standards. The director's decision shall be final and he shall have authority to enforce and make effective such decisions. Appeals of the director's decisions may be made pursuant to Chapter 17.98 of this code. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,344,Calaveras_County.pdf,196
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.200 - Geometric design (FIRE).,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.200 - Geometric design (FIRE).
A. Vertical Curves. Length of vertical curves shall be determined from the Highway Design Manual, employing the graphs and calculations therein for safe stopping distance. The minimum length of vertical curve shall be one hundred feet unless approved by the director. At elevations of three thousand feet and greater, intersection approaches shall accommodate two cars on a road grade of five percent or less. B. Horizontal Curves. Radii and lengths of horizontal curves shall be determined from Chapter 200 of the Highway Design Manual. Curves shall have a radius of not less than one hundred feet, and all switchback areas shall have a road grade not exceeding five percent. All horizontal curve radii shall meet the requirements for superelevation and design speed on major and minor collector roads. Private collectors, locals, residential and commercial/industrial roads shall have superelevation as determined by the engineer. Superelevation is not required in community areas. C. Superelevation. The rate of superelevation shall be a maximum of four one-hundredths (0.04) feet per foot above the three thousand foot elevation and six one-hundredths (0.06) feet per foot at the three thousand foot elevation or below. D. Crown. The rate of crown for all roads shall be two one-hundredths (0.02) feet per foot, with the exception of gravel and earth roads, which shall have a crown of three one-hundredths (0.03) feet per foot. E. Fill and Cut Slope Ratio. Fill slopes shall not be steeper than 1.5:1 and cut slopes not steeper than one to one (1:1). When supported by laboratory tests, cut and fill slopes shall be subject to the approval of the director. Flatter fill slopes may be required and steeper cut slopes may be allowed when soil conditions warrant. F. Structural Section. Designing of structural sections shall be in accordance with Section 600 of the Design Manual with a safety factor of 0.00. Traffic index (TI) shall be as set forth in this chapter. The director may require greater TI's for collector roads when special circumstances exist. R-value tests of subgrade shall be performed by an approved laboratory. G. Ditch Side Slope Ratio. All ditch side slopes from roadway shoulder to bottom of the ditch shall be three to one (3:1) or flatter. H. Ditch Depth. Off-road ditch sections shall be calculated from hydraulic data prepared by an engineer and have a minimum of one foot depth. I. Width of Base Application. Base material for undivided paved roads shall be applied to the full width required in Section 12.02.150 of this chapter. J. All Paved Typical Road Sections. All paved typical road sections shall be allowed on all roads in lieu of the typical road sections set forth in this chapter. The location, limits and transitions into and out of all paved road sections shall be set forth on the improvement plans. All paved typical road sections shall be as set forth in the standard details. Storm drainage systems shall be designed compatible with an all-paved section. K. Widths of Right-of-Way. 1. Sufficient width of right-of-way shall be provided to contain the template. For all public roads without curb and gutters, the minimum right-of-way shall be five feet beyond the catch points (top of cut, toe of fill). 2. When reduced rights-of-way are proposed and approved, such approvals may preclude, inhibit or reduce the potential for further subdivision or long-range development of parcels deriving access from the road. Long-range development plans should be considered when requesting a reduction in right-of-way width. L. Road Grades. 1. The minimum profile road grade for all roads shall be one percent. On paved roads with curb and gutter, the profile grade may be reduced to one-half percent. 2. The maximum road grade for all roads shall be shown in accordance with Sections 12.02.150 through 12.02.170 of this chapter. M. Sidewalks shall be four and one-half feet wide in residential areas, five and one-half feet wide in industrial areas and seven and one-half feet wide in commercial areas. Sidewalks shall be constructed of Class B concrete, unless otherwise approved by the director. When permitted by the commission or an applicable community, special or specific plan, pedestrian pathways may be substituted for sidewalks. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,344,Calaveras_County.pdf,922
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.210 - Drainage.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.210 - Drainage.
A. All drainage facilities shall be designed to conform to Chapter 800 of the Highway Design Manual. Drainage improvements shall control the flow of surface water on and across a road in accordance with accepted engineering practices. The facilities for roadway drainage consists of ditches, curbs and gutters and the road surface. The project proponent may propose alternate methods of drainage control, which, upon approval of the director, may be substituted for curbs and gutters. Above the three thousand foot elevation, alternate methods are preferred to raised curbs. B. Curb, Gutter Design. The design of curbs and gutters and necessary storm drains shall be in accordance with the Highway Design Manual; the need for such improvements shall be determined on an individual basis to meet drainage requirements in and through the project. Roll curb may be used on community roads where approved by the director. C. Culvert Design. The minimum diameter for culvert pipes crossing roads shall be eighteen inches. The minimum diameter for a private driveway (side drain) culvert shall be twelve inches. A basis for culvert design shall be design flood, employing the rule: 1. That a culvert pass a ten-year flood without static head above the crown of culvert at its entrance; 2. That culverts and appurtenances shall be designed to pass the one-hundred-year flood without overtopping. D. Site Drainage and Off-Site Drainage. An engineering design for on-site and off-site drainage shall be submitted with improvement plans. Energy dissipators and other drainage control devices shall be employed as needed to prevent scour in swales and intermittent drainage channels. Detention ponds may be constructed to prevent downstream flooding. E. Closed Storm Drain Design. Improvement projects and subdivisions shall be protected from inundation, flood hazard, sheet overflow and ponding of local storm water, springs and other surface waters. The design of improvements shall be such that water accumulating within the project will be carried away from the project without injury to any adjacent improvements, residential sites or residences to be constructed on sites within the project, or to adjoining areas. Water accumulating within the project shall be carried to storm drainage facilities or to a natural watercourse by closed circuit or as allowed by this section to meet the design standards herein set forth. Drainage design within the project shall accommodate anticipated future development within the drainage area. Any off-site drainage facilities required to carry storm water from the proposed project to a defined channel or existing conduit shall be made adequate for ultimate development of the drainage area. The diversion of natural drainage will be allowed only within the limits of the proposed improvement. All natural drainage must enter and leave the improved area at its original horizontal and vertical alignment unless an agreement, approved by the director, has been executed with the adjoining property owners. F. Bridge and Box Culvert Design. Bridges shall be designed in conformance with Caltrans Highway Design Manual Chapter 800 and shall pass the one-hundred-year flow with a minimum of two feet freeboard. Concrete box culverts shall be designed to pass the one-hundred-year flood without overtopping of the roadway. Complete plans and design calculations for bridges and culverts shall be included in the improvement plans. Bridges shall be designed for legal highway loadings. Maximum legal highway loadings shall be used on all major collectors and through roads. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,345,Calaveras_County.pdf,689
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.220 - Erosion control.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.220 - Erosion control.
An erosion control plan is required and must be approved by the director. This requirement may be waived by the director. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,346,Calaveras_County.pdf,39
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.230 - Cul-de-sac (FIRE).,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.230 - Cul-de-sac (FIRE).
A. All cul-de-sacs shall meet the following requirements: 1. A surface diameter of eighty feet; 2. An eighty-four-foot diameter roadbed; 3. A one-hundred-foot diameter right-of-way; 4. Maximum cumulative length shall not exceed: Lot Size Maximum Length Less than 1 acre 800 feet 1 to 4.99 acres 1,320 feet 5 to 19.99 acres 2,640 feet 20 acres or over 5,280 feet B. Intermediate turnarounds shall be required at one thousand three hundred twenty foot intervals when a cul-de-sac exceeds that length. C. A hammer-head turnaround may be permitted by the director in lieu of a cul-de-sac with concurrence of the responsible fire protection agency. Hammer-head turnarounds shall be constructed in accordance with the county standard detail. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,346,Calaveras_County.pdf,194
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.240 - Street names.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.240 - Street names.
All roads and streets shall be named on the final or parcel map subject to the approval of the building department. Proposed names shall not duplicate or too closely approximate, phonetically, the names of any other road in the county. When roads are a continuation of existing roads, the existing road name shall be used. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,347,Calaveras_County.pdf,78
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.250 - Signs and striping.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.250 - Signs and striping.
A. All roads shall be properly signed and striped. Signing and striping limits shall be set forth in improvement plans. B. (FIRE). Road name signs shall be placed at each intersection, visible from both directions of vehicular travel. Road name signs shall be a minimum of four inches letter height, three-eighths-inch stroke, reflectorized and shall be placed on a contrasting background. C. Traffic control devices and signs of approved design shall be placed as delineated in the improvement plans. The need for such signs shall be determined on an individual basis in accordance with the latest edition of the traffic manual, or as determined by the director. D. Signs signifying roads which are not in the county-maintained road system shall be installed at intersections with roads in the maintained system. Such signs shall read ""NOT A COUNTY-MAINTAINED ROAD"" and shall be a minimum eighteen- inch by twenty-four-inch rectangular, standard black on white regulatory sign unless otherwise specified in the standard details. E. Other warning signs may be required by the director based on specific project design features. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,347,Calaveras_County.pdf,237
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.260 - Intersections.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.260 - Intersections.
A. All roads shall intersect at right angles (ninety degrees) and shall have at least fifty feet of tangent adjacent to the intersection. Where conditions of terrain dictate, the intersection angle may be reduced, to not less than sixty degrees with approval of the director. B. Any two roads entering upon a given road from opposite directions shall have a common centerline; otherwise the point of intersection shall be separated by a minimum of one hundred fifty feet if the intersected street is a local road, three hundred feet if the intersected street is a minor collector road and five hundred feet if the intersected street is a major collector road. C. Intersection design shall be in accordance with the standard details adopted by the board of supervisors. D. At the intersections with state highways, a state encroachment permit shall be required and state requirements shall be satisfied. E. Driveway encroachments shall be located no closer than twenty feet from intersection returns on local and residential public roads and all private roads. On all other roads it shall be no closer than one hundred feet unless approved by the director. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ARTICLE IV. - PLAN SUBMITTAL PROCEDURES AND IMPROVEMENT SECURITY ",Calaveras_County,348,Calaveras_County.pdf,254
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.270 - Plans and speci␀cations.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.270 - Plans and speci␀cations.
Plans and specifications for all required improvements shall be submitted to the department in such form prescribed by the written department guidelines. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,348,Calaveras_County.pdf,39
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.280 - Plans.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.280 - Plans.
Improvement plans shall conform to the provisions of this chapter, except for minimum service roads and for projects in which private roads already exist. In such cases, an engineer shall certify, in writing, that such private roads and maximum service roads have been constructed or presently exist to the standards set forth in this chapter. The certification shall be made in writing prior to release of security, if any, or filing of a final or parcel map. Such written certifications are subject to the review and approval of the director. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,348,Calaveras_County.pdf,117
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,"12.02.290 - Standard details, construction standards and material testing.","Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.290 - Standard details, construction standards and material testing.
A. Standard county details, construction standards and material testing requirements shall be as specified by the department's written standards and shall be adopted by resolution of the board of supervisors. B. All developments that require utility improvements shall conform with the following: 1. Construction. a. Public Agency Facilities. Utility design and installation shall meet the requirements of the public agency or utility that will accept and maintain the facilities. Installation shall also meet county requirements for depth of cover (thirty-six inches minimum), ""R-value"" and pavement structural section, trench width and required backfill with a two-sack minimum cement-sand slurry unless an alternate method is approved in advance by the director. b. Private Facilities. Utilities to be maintained by a district or agency not yet formed shall be designed by an engineer. and installation shall comply with all applicable state and local laws and regulations. 2. Security. The installation and maintenance for a period of one year for all utility facilities shall be secured by a satisfactory instrument along with other required project improvements pursuant to this chapter and Titles 16 and 17 of the Calaveras County Code. Security in accordance with this section shall be provided to the public agency responsible for the facility. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,348,Calaveras_County.pdf,259
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.300 - Construction inspection.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.300 - Construction inspection.
A. All improvements shall be periodically inspected during construction by the department. The director shall have access to the work to ascertain that the materials and workmanship are in accordance with the requirements of this chapter, the standard specifications and the approved improvement plans. Prior to proceeding to subsequent phases, each phase shall obtain necessary inspection approvals. The order of phases of construction shall be as follows, unless a variance of this schedule is approved in advance by the director: 1. Construction staking; 2. Completion of subgrade; 3. Installation of drainage structures and utilities; 4. Aggregate subbase, where required; 5. Aggregate base; 6. Surfacing; 7. Cleanup. B. Any substandard work or materials employed in the work and all work done contrary to the provisions of this chapter shall be repaired or replaced as directed by the department. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,349,Calaveras_County.pdf,191
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.310 - Cleanup.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.310 - Cleanup.
All areas of the work shall be cleaned of all debris and excess materials. All portions of the work shall be left in a neat and orderly condition satisfactory to the director. All brush and debris from any right-of-way clearing shall be disposed in a manner approved by the department. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,349,Calaveras_County.pdf,71
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.320 - Final inspection.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.320 - Final inspection.
Upon completion of all improvements, the applicant or project contractor shall notify the director of completion. The applicant shall submit to the director a written request for final approval. After final inspection, if the work has been completed in accordance with this chapter, the director shall notify the applicant and the applicant shall submit as-built plans to the county for approval. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,349,Calaveras_County.pdf,84
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.330 - As-built plans.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.330 - As-built plans.
As-built plans are required. The director may, at his discretion, waive this requirement. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,349,Calaveras_County.pdf,34
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.340 - Improvement security and agreement.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.340 - Improvement security and agreement.
A. When project improvements are not completed at the time the final or parcel map is ready for approval by the county surveyor, the applicant shall enter into a project improvement agreement with the county. The agreement shall require the applicant to complete all improvements as shown on the approved improvement plans within the time set forth therein. B. Applicant's performance under any such agreement shall be secured by a good and sufficient instrument of surety in an amount fixed by the estimated costs of the improvements in accordance with Table VIII of this section. The estimate of construction costs shall be submitted to the director for approval. Security for county-maintained road improvements shall provide that ten percent of the secured amount be withheld by the county for a period of one year after the completion of improvements. The ten percent retention may be used by the county to correct any defects in material or workmanship which become evident in the one-year-period following completion. C. Security required for project improvements shall be as follows: Table VIII AMOUNT OF AGREEMENT SECURITY Type of Security Performance Labor/ Materials Total Bonds 100% 100% 200% Letter of credit 75% 75% 150% Bank deposit (1) 75% 75% 150% Deposit with county (2) 75% 50% 125% (1) Savings account assigned to the county. (2) Deposit in a trust account or a negotiable certificate of deposit with principal payable to the county upon demand. D. Termination date of any security shall extend beyond the termination date of the agreement or any extension thereof. Termination date shall be subject to the requirements of the director. E. Bank Deposits, Certificates of Deposit. 1. Such deposits shall be purchased or an account opened so that the principal and interest are payable to the ""County of Calaveras."" 2. If the account or certificate is made jointly payable to the applicant and the county, the applicant shall submit a negotiable order of withdrawal with the bank book or an endorsed certificate. F. The letter of credit shall be extended prior to its expiration date for any extension of time requested. G. Security will be released upon request of the project proponent in accordance with the terms of this section and the ""project improvement agreement"" or ""subdivision improvement agreement."" H. Upon written request by the applicant, no less than thirty days prior to the expiration of the agreement, an extension of time may be requested from the board of supervisors. The applicant shall have made a good faith effort to complete improvement requirements, or weather conditions or litigation shall have prevented completion of the improvements. An extension of time of up to one year may be approved, provided the improvement security is adjusted subject to approval of the director. I. Performance Bond. Performance bonds shall be required for the estimated amount of the work to ensure satisfactory completion. Performance bonds must be provided by an admitted California surety. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,350,Calaveras_County.pdf,602
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.350 - Inspection fee.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.350 - Inspection fee.
A. The applicant shall deposit an estimated fee to cover the county's actual costs of inspection of the project. This fee may be deposited in two installments. The first installment shall be paid when plans are submitted for checking. The balance of the inspection fee shall be deposited prior to the start of work. B. Inspection includes field inspection during the course of construction and certain materials testing of those improvements over which no other public agency or utility exercises inspection responsibility. All other public agency or utility fees shall be paid separately by the applicant. The estimated inspection fee of the department shall be calculated in accordance with the following schedule: Table IX INSPECTION FEE DEPOSIT Total Estimated Cost of Plan Check Inspection Total Improvements Less than $10,000 $ 300.00 $1,200.00 $1,500.00 $ 10,000 to $ 49,999 $ 500.00 $2,000.00 $2,500.00 $ 50,000 to $ 99,999 $1,000.00 $5,000.00 $6,000.00 $100,000 to $399,999 1% $6,000.00 $6,000.00 + 1% $400,000 and over 1% 1.5% 2.5% C. The deposit shall be placed in the road commissioner's trust fund and all charges for inspection as deemed necessary by the director shall be charged against that fund. No inspection work or construction work shall be undertaken if the cost of such inspection or work exceeds the funds remaining in the trust account for the project. D. Whenever the deposit is exhausted, the applicant shall deposit additional funds for further inspection work. In the event that the total inspection charges are less than the deposit, the balance will be returned to the applicant after the improvements have been certified as complete by the director. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ARTICLE V. - ADDITIONAL PROVISIONS ",Calaveras_County,351,Calaveras_County.pdf,408
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.360 - Special provisions by board resolution.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.360 - Special provisions by board resolution.
A. The board may, by resolution, adopt more specific standards for road improvements consistent herewith, and may define a more specific application and/or construction than this chapter. B. The board may, by resolution, adopt precise policies related to road improvements in areas in which there are special circumstances warranting more precise policies. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,352,Calaveras_County.pdf,80
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.370 - Maintenance.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.370 - Maintenance.
A. Provisions for maintenance shall be required for all public and private roads serving all projects except minimum service roads serving only two parcels as approved after the effective date of the ordinance codified in this chapter, regardless of when the project was submitted for county review and consideration. The maintenance provisions shall be consistent with subsections (B) or (C) of this section. B. The commission may require the formation of, or annexation to, a special district providing road maintenance and improvement. In such case, a final map shall not be filed, and no building permit shall be issued until the local agency formation commission (LAFCO) has approved such annexation or formation and a certificate of completion has been recorded by the executive officer of LAFCO. C. The commission may require the applicant to execute and record agreements for maintenance and improvement of public and private roads serving the project prior to the filing of the final map or the issuance of a building permit, encroachment permit or certificate of use and occupancy. Such agreement shall be in a form approved by the director and shall contain the following provisions and any additional provisions deemed necessary by the commission or director: 1. A requirement that all property owners be members; 2. A provision permitting a simple majority of the members to impose road maintenance fees on all parcels included in the agreement; 3. A means for collection of fees imposed; 4. Authorization for fees collected to be used for road maintenance or improvement on the roads specified in the agreement; 5. Identification of all roads subject to the agreement; 6. A provision providing a means by which additional property owners may join the agreement; 7. Authorization for a majority of parties to the agreement to enforce its provisions on any or all of the other members; 8. A provision stating that the obligations imposed by the agreement run with the land. (Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). ",Calaveras_County,352,Calaveras_County.pdf,393
"Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES",Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE,12.02.380 - Modi␀cations and appeals.,"Calaveras_County | Title 12 - STREETS, SIDEWALKS AND PUBLIC PLACES | Chapter 12.02 - ROAD CONSTRUCTION AND MAINTENANCE | 12.02.380 - Modi␀cations and appeals.
A. The planning commission may consider modifications to the minimum standards imposed by the director or set forth in this chapter when it appears necessary, reasonable, and proper, and provided the health, safety, and welfare of the public is not effected and the use of the public right-of-way is not detrimentally effected. B. All requests for modifications shall be in writing and must be submitted to the planning director prior to any planning commission consideration of the request. The request shall state and describe all modifications to the applicable standards and shall include all relevant data and facts establishing the grounds for which the modification is requested, and be accompanied by written justification and a statement by a licensed engineer that traffic safety is not compromised. C. The commission may approve a modification to the standards based upon the following criteria: 1. There are physical characteristics unique to the property, including size, shape, topography, location or surroundings that are so unusual that complying with the requirements of this chapter would create an exceptional hardship to the applicant or the surrounding property owners or create practical difficulties. 2. There is an overwhelming community preference to maintain an existing condition. 3. Financial motivation as sole justification for a modification will not be approved. D. Approval of any modification shall be supported by findings based upon evidence in the administrative record. E. The commission may impose such terms and conditions as it deems necessary. F. Any action of the planning commission related to these road improvement standards may be appealed to the board of supervisors in accordance with the procedures defined in Chapter 17.98 of this code. (Ord. 2599 § 3, 1999: Ord. 2295 § 2(part), 1992). (Ord. No. 2968, 8-11-2009) ",Calaveras_County,352,Calaveras_County.pdf,360
